<AU>   FBIS-EAS-94-100 </AU>
Daily Report 
<DATE1>  18 May 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> Vietnam </F>
<H3> <TI>   Successes in Recruiting New Party Members Noted </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Successes in Recruiting New Party Members Noted </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   BK2005122694 Hanoi Voice of Vietnam Network in Vietnamese 
0500 GMT 18 May 94 </F>

<F P=103> BK2005122694 </F>
<F P=104>  Hanoi Voice of Vietnam Network </F>
<F P=105>  Vietnamese </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Implementing the party Central Committee's third 
plenum resolution on renovating and revamping the party, the 
nation has made encouraging achievements over the past two years 
in its efforts to train and develop newly-recruited party 
members. Almost 50,000 new party members were admitted during 
1993, an increase of 38 percent over the previous year. Among 
these, 43 percent were admitted by grassroots party 
organizations, the highest percentage in several years. 
  The An Giang provincial party organization has concentrated 
its efforts on developing party chapters in hamlets and housing 
clusters. In 1993, about 50 percent of the province's 
newly-recruited party members came from rural areas. Many came 
from 21 of the 26 hamlets that had never before admitted party 
members. 
  Party organizations in Thai Binh and Hai Hung Provinces also 
admitted more members as a result of their efforts in holding 
refresher courses for cadres responsible for recruiting new 
party members. 
  Party organizations in the Army have paid special attention 
to recruiting officers, non-commissioned officers, and national 
defense and professional personnel. In 1993, the Army admitted 
more than 8,000 new party members, 95 percent of them under the 
age of 30. 

</TEXT>

