<F P=100> Brunei, Malaysia &amp; Singapore </F>
<F P=101> Malaysia </F>
<H3> <TI>   PRC Official Says Country To Import More Goods </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    PRC Official Says Country To Import More Goods </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   BK2405110994 Kuala Lumpur Voice of Malaysia in English 0800 
GMT 24 May 94 </F>

<F P=103> BK2405110994 </F>
<F P=104>  Kuala Lumpur Voice of Malaysia </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] China intends to purchase more goods from Malaysia, 
especially commodities such as processed palm oil and crude 
petroleum as well as food products. China's State Planning 
Commission Vice Chairman, Encik [Mr.] Gan Ziyu said China would 
like to improve its imports from Malaysia because the momentum 
for the economic growth of 9 percent in China is still high. He 
told newsmen this after calling on Deputy Minister of 
International Trade and Industry, Encik Chua Jui Meng in Kuala 
Lumpur. 
  China is also interested to import the commodities and food 
products through more direct trade with Malaysia. At the same 
time, it plans to improve its exports of edible oils, textile 
machinery, and fabrics to Malaysia. 
  Gan said China's exports to Malaysia in 1993 increased by 21 
percent over the previous year while at the same time its 
imports rose by 30 percent. Bilateral trade between Malaysia 
and China grew by 500 percent between 1985 and 1993. Malaysia's 
exports of commodities such as processed palm oil, crude 
petroleum, natural rubber and cacao made up 78 percent of total 
exports to China. 

</TEXT>

