<F P=100> South Korea </F>
<H3> <TI>   ROK Said Opposed to DPRK `Peace Treaty' Proposal </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    ROK Said Opposed to DPRK `Peace Treaty' Proposal </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   SK2405023294 Seoul YONHAP in English 0214 GMT 24 May 94 </F>
<F P=103> SK2405023294 </F>
<F P=104>  Seoul YONHAP </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Seoul, May 24 (YONHAP) -- South Korea is poised to 
inform the United States of its position that it is firmly 
opposed to North Korea's proposal for replacing the Korean 
armistice agreement with a peace treaty being discussed in 
U.S.-North Korea talks, according to Deputy Prime Minister Yi 
Hong-ku Monday. 
  Yi told the National Assembly Foreign Affairs and National 
Unification Committee the government will convey such position 
at Seoul-Washington working-level meetings to be held in the 
U.S. capital soon in preparation for a third round of high-level 
talks between the United States and North Korea. 
  Yi said, "substituting the armistice agreement with a peace 
accord cannot be an issue to be discussed between the United 
States and North Korea, and this point will be reiterated to the 
U.S. Government by Nuclear Affairs Ambassador Kim Sam-hun, who 
is currently visiting Washington." 
  Yi, also the national unification minister, made the remarks 
while replying to lawmakers' questions on the possibility that 
North Korea may demand a peace accord. 
  The South Korean Government has devised its policy based on 
an analysis of North Korea's strategy in demanding a U.S. troop 
withdrawal from Korea. 
  Government officials said the issue of a peace accord should 
be addressed by the South and North Koreans in accordance with 
the basic South-North agreement signed in 1992. Until that 
time, the present armistice accord should be strictly observed, 
they stressed. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS4-53922 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "dreas100_d_94002" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-EAS-94-100 </AU>
Daily Report 
<DATE1>  24 May 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> South Korea </F>
<H3> <TI>   U.S., DPRK Reportedly Hold Working-Level Contact </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    U.S., DPRK Reportedly Hold Working-Level Contact </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   SK2405024194 Seoul YONHAP in English 0151 GMT 24 May 94 </F>
<F P=103> SK2405024194 </F>
<F P=104>  Seoul YONHAP </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Washington, May 23 (YONHAP) -- The United States, 
looking to hold a third round of negotiations with North Korea 
in early June, held a working-level contact in New York Monday 
afternoon to prepare for the proposed talks. 
  Meanwhile, the South Korean ambassador in charge of nuclear 
affairs, Kim Sam-hun, met with Robert Gallucci, chairman of the 
Clinton Administration Policy Group on Korea, to coordinate 
their countries' positions on the next round of 
Washington-Pyongyang high-level talks. 
  In New York, the U.S. side was said to have proposed a date 
for the negotiations after reiterating its conditions for the 
talks. 
  Depending on North Korea's attitude, there is a strong 
possibility the talks could be held in early June, sources said. 
  State Department Spokesman Mike McCurry confirmed that an 
unofficial contact with North Korea had taken place in New York. 
McCurry also said that Gallucci, in addition to his meeting 
with Kim Sam-hun, is expected to hold several days of talks with 
officials from Japan and China on the North Korean nuclear 
dispute in New York beginning Tuesday. 
  Speaking at a regular weekly press briefing, McCurry said 
that if North Korea could agree with the International Atomic 
Energy Agency (IAEA) on the question of maintaining nuclear 
safeguards, there would be no obstacle to the third round of 
talks. 
  "The IAEA's ability to conduct the activities it needs to 
maintain safeguards on spent fuel -- as long as that is 
preserved, we would see no obstacle to another round of 
high-level talks," McCurry said. 
  The spokesman called on Pyongyang to accommodate the 
activities of the IAEA inspection team as soon as possible. 
  "We certainly urge North Korea to agree to the procedures 
the 
IAEA needs as soon as possible and not to jeopardize the IAEA's 
ability to conduct activities necessary to maintain safeguards 
on the spent fuel," he said. 
  The United States has not decided on the date for the third 
round of talks, McCurry said. 
  "We wouldn't proceed to announcing a date without a full 
range of consultations with others that we share an interest in 
this subject with," he added. "That would include the Government 
of Japan and obviously South Korea." 
  But one senior State Department official said further talks 
with Pyongyang could be held early next month, when the two 
countries are expected to discuss the nuclear issue as well as 
problems related to normalizing political and trade relations. 
  Following his meeting with Gallucci, South Korean Ambassador 
Kim hinted that the conditions for third-round talks between 
Washington and Pyongyang have pratically been satisfied. 
Specifically, Kim said the principal condition for the talks is 
additional IAEA inspection of a key radiochemical laboratory and 
servicing of surveillance equipment. 
  As for the refueling of the 5-megawatt reactor at Yongbyon, 
Kim said that if North Korea continued to remove spent fuel 
rods, the basis for dialogue could "collapse." But discussions 
on the refueling between the IAEA and Pyongyang can proceed in 
parallel with the U.S.-North Korea talks if measurement of the 
spent fuel rods by the IAEA later is guaranteed, Kim said. 
  McCurry said that should the discharge of fuel from the 
5-megawatt reactor continue without any of the IAEA's proposed 
steps being in place, then North Korea would inevitably 
undermine the basis for dialogue. 
  "We'd have no choice but to return the matter to the United 
Nations Security Council," he said. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS4-53923 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "dreas100_d_94003" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-EAS-94-100 </AU>
Daily Report 
<DATE1>  24 May 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> South Korea </F>
<H3> <TI>   ROK Nuclear Ambassador, Gallucci Hold Talks </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    ROK Nuclear Ambassador, Gallucci Hold Talks </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   SK2405070294 Seoul YONHAP in English 0628 GMT 24 May 94 </F>
<F P=103> SK2405070294 </F>
<F P=104>  Seoul YONHAP </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Washington, May 24 (YONHAP) -- Kim Sam-hun, South 
Korea's nuclear ambassador who is currently visiting the United 
States, said Monday the North Korean nuclear fuel rod problem is 
one basis of Pyongyang-Washington high-level talks but not a 
precondition to the dialogue. 
  Kim made the remark after meeting with Robert Gallucci, U.S. 
assistant secretary of State for Political and Military Affairs, 
to discuss the North Korean nuclear problem and 
Pyongyang-Washington talks for about four and a half hours at 
the State Department. 
  He indicated that conditions for U.S.-North Korea high-level 
talks have virtually been met, saying, "The direct conditions 
for the talks are additional inspections by the International 
Atomic Energy Agency (IAEA) of the radiochemical laboratory and 
follow-up inspections on maintenance of the IAEA's monitoring 
equipment. 
  "As far as I know, the IAEA's additional inspection has been 
carried out smoothly." 
  He noted that solving the fuel rod problem at the 5-megawatt 
reactor in Yongbyon is not a precondition to the third round of 
dialogue but a basis on which Pyongyang and Washington can 
continue bilateral talks. 
  "The basis can be prepared only when North Korea stops 
replacing the fuel rods or accepts the IAEA position, which 
demands selection, storage and measurement of the fuel, or 
agrees with the IAEA to secure measurement in any form after a 
certain period. 
  "If North Korea pushes to withdraw fuel rods from the 
reactor 
unilaterally, the basis of the talks is feared to collapse at a 
certain point in time," he said. 
  IAEA officials have already confirmed that Pyongyang 
replaced 
some fuel rods at the 5-megawatt reactor without outside 
supervision, while another IAEA team is to arrive in Pyongyang 
on Tuesday to negotiate supervision of further refueling. 
  He also hinted that the IAEA-North Korean negotiations on 
fuel rods and the Pyongyang-Washington talks could be carried 
out side by side. 
  Kim's comments suggest that the United States will push for 
a 
third round of high-level talks unless the IAEA officially 
announces that North Korea's fuel rod replacement has already 
passed over the "red line," even if the fuel rod negotiations 
take much time. He added that it is up to the IAEA to determine 
the "red line" up to which measurement of the fuel rods is 
secured. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

