<F P=100> South Korea </F>
<H3> <TI>   Trade Official on USTR Actions in Sausage Dispute </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Trade Official on USTR Actions in Sausage Dispute </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   SK2205043694 Seoul YONHAP in English 0409 GMT 22 May 94 </F>
<F P=103> SK2205043694 </F>
<F P=104>  Seoul YONHAP </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Seoul, May 22 (YONHAP) -- Washington has begun to 
look into the damages on its industry following Seoul's virtual 
ban on American sausage imports at the recommendation by U.S. 
sausage producers to invoke Super 301 trade sanctions against 
Korea, a trade official here said Sunday. 
  The U.S. Trade Representative (USTR) recently asked sausage 
manufacturers to submit details of their damages resulting from 
Korea's massive disposal of American sausages, the official said. 
  USTR also requested the producers to state their complaints 
and recommendations following Korea's shortening of shelf life 
to 30 days from former 90 days. 
  The American Sausage Producers Association had advised 
Washington to designate Korea as a priority foreign country in 
accordance with the Super 301 trade act for Seoul's cutting 
shelf life of American products and then disposing of them on 
the grounds that they are hazardous to public health. 
  "I think USTR began to investigate into the problem in order 
to present documental proof that Korea's action was unfair in 
future trade talks," the official said. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

