<F P=100> South Korea </F>
<H3> <TI>   Government To Protect North Korean Refugees </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Government To Protect North Korean Refugees </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   SK2305110294 Seoul YONHAP in English 0750 GMT 23 May 94 </F>
<F P=103> SK2305110294 </F>
<F P=104>  Seoul YONHAP </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Seoul, May 23 (YONHAP) -- The government has made 
the first decision to protect five North Koreans who sought 
refuge in South Korea several months ago under the related law 
which came into effect last Dec. 11, officials said Monday. 
  According to "the law to protect the North Korean 
compatriots 
who sought refuge in the South," the government should convene a 
committee of officials from related ministries to decide whether 
to assist North Koreans within 30 days of their request for 
protection from the health and social affairs minister. 
  The committee, sponsored by the Health and Social Affairs 
Ministry, recently decided to offer protection to four North 
Korean escapees from Siberian logging camps including Kim 
Kil-song, 31, and Kwon Ki-hae, 53, who fled North Korea through 
a third country. 
  Under the law, the government will give each refuge seeker 
14.7 million won (about 18,300 U.S. dollars) for resettlement 
and 7 million won to rent a small apartment. 
  The decision is attracting attention because more North 
Koreans have been seeking refuge in the South recently, the 
officials said. 

</TEXT>

