<F P=100> South Korea </F>
<H3> <TI>   President Welcomes Russian Proposal on Conference </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    President Welcomes Russian Proposal on Conference </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   SK2405074394 Seoul YONHAP in English 0720 GMT 24 May 94 </F>
<F P=103> SK2405074394 </F>
<F P=104>  Seoul YONHAP </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Seoul, May 24 (YONHAP) -- President Kim Yong-sam 
reportedly said Monday North Korea should give up its nuclear 
program and try to solve problems on the Korean peninsula 
through dialogue with South Korea as well as the United States. 
  President Kim made the statement in answer to a question on 
what message he wants to send to North Korea through his June 
1-4 visit to Russia at a press conference with Russian 
correspondents here Monday. 
  Kim was known to have welcomed Moscow's proposal on holding 
an international conference attended by South and North Korea, 
Russia, China, Japan, the United States, the United Nations and 
the International Atomic Energy Agency (IAEA) as an expression 
of its intention to find a solution to the North Korean nuclear 
problem. 
  He added, however, that it will take a little longer for 
these parties to determine whether such a conference would 
efficiently help settle the nuclear dispute. 
  Noting that he believes Russia is firmly opposed to North 
Korea's production of nuclear weapons, Kim said he will study 
ways to cooperate in the nuclear issue at summit meetings with 
Russian President Boris Yeltsin. 

</TEXT>

