<F P=100> South Korea </F>
<H3> <TI>   Embassy Says SRV To Return ROK Community Center </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Embassy Says SRV To Return ROK Community Center </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   SK2205090894 Seoul YONHAP in English 0736 GMT 22 May 94 </F>
<F P=103> SK2205090894 </F>
<F P=104>  Seoul YONHAP </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Ho Chi Minh, May 22 (YONHAP) -- The former Korean 
Community Center in Ho Chi Minh is expected to be returned to 
South Korea next month, an official at the Korean Embassy in 
Vietnam said Sunday. The consulate general in Ho Chi Minh has 
been demanding quick return of the property and the city has 
recently notified that it will hand over the building within the 
first half of the year, the official said. 
  The government reportedly plans to use the site as cultural 
center and school for Koreans in Vietnam. An estimated 800 
Koreans, including diplamats and expatriates, live here and 
education problem for their children may be resolved to some 
extent if the center is turned into a school, the official said. 
The 162-pyong [one pyong is six square feet] two-storey building 
had been used as a school and Taekwondo gym until 1975 when 
Korean troops withdrew from Saigon after if fell to communism 
and broke diplomatic ties. Seoul and Hanoi restored full 
relations in December 1992. 
  Koreans here have to send their children to expensive 
international schools in Malaysia, Taiwan or Singapore because 
there are no Korean schools in Vietnam. 

</TEXT>

