<F P=101> Japan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Hata on Consumption Tax, Political Landscape </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Hata on Consumption Tax, Political Landscape </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   OW2405043194 Tokyo KYODO in English 0350 GMT 24 May 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW2405043194 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo KYODO </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Tokyo, May 24 KYODO -- Prime Minister Tsutomu Hata 
strongly indicated Tuesday that the government will move to 
raise the consumption tax from the current 3 percent in the 
planned sweeping tax reform. 
  Hata told the budget committee of the House of 
Representatives that the tax burden should be spread thinly and 
shouldered by as many people as possible in order to secure 
fiscal resources in the face of the rapidly aging society. 
  He said the tax rate on consumption in Japan is the lowest 
among the 25 nations belonging to the Organization for Economic 
Cooperation and Development (OECD). 
  The remarks are the latest signal of the government's 
intention to boost the ratio of indirect tax in the taxation 
reform that the government has pledged to realize by the end of 
the year. 
  The draft bills for the reform are scheduled to be compiled 
by the end of June. 
  Hata also reiterated the next general election should be 
held 
under the new electoral system. 
  A government panel is drawing up a new electoral map in line 
with the political reform law passed in January, which 
stipulates the replacement of the current multiseat 
constituencies with a system of combined single-seat 
constituencies and proportional representation. 
  Hata, who leads the first minority government in four 
decades, has repeatedly dismissed opposition calls for snap 
polls under the old system to restore stable government. 
  Over questions of the economic conditions, Yoshio Terasawa, 
Economic Planning Agency director general, said the nation's 
economy has yet to get back on a recovery path. 
  Terasawa, while pointing to some bright signs, said the 
economy is by and large in a slump, with capital investments, 
corporate earnings and the employment picture remaining weak. 
  Asked about his view on the political realignment, Hata said 
he is looking for a change to a bipolar political landscape with 
the Liberal Democratic Party (LDP) and a counteralliance as the 
two major players. 
  He said the policy gap between the Social Democratic Party 
(SDP) [Social Democratic Party of Japan, SDPJ] and its partners 
in the ruling coalition under former Prime Minister Morihiro 
Hosokawa has narrowed through policy discussions. 
  With the LDP being one major power, it is hoped that the two 
leading players will control the political scene, Hata said. 
  The SDP walked out of the coalition after it was infuriated 
by the formation of a new Diet group by some coalition members 
without consulting the SDP. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

