<F P=101> Japan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Progress in National Development Plan Cited </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Progress in National Development Plan Cited </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   OW2305111794 Tokyo KYODO in English 1016 GMT 23 May 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW2305111794 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo KYODO </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Tokyo, May 23 KYODO -- More than half of the heads 
of local autonomies and economic organizations feel the 
government's comprehensive national development plan aimed at 
administrative decentralization has failed to accomplish its 
ultimate goal, a survey by KYODO NEWS SERVICE showed Monday [23 
May]. 
  The heads of 22 local governments and seven economic 
federations out of 23 autonomies and eight economic groups 
polled responded to the poll, which was conducted in late April. 
  The survey showed that 59 percent of those polled felt the 
goal of decentralizing the government has not been achieved 
totally or substantially. 
  They based their responses on the wide gap between Tokyo and 
local municipalities in such fields as population density, 
economies and information propagation. 
  About two-thirds of respondents said some achievements have 
been made in the four national development plans implemented 
since 1962. 
  An overwhelming majority of leaders of local autonomies 
called for the carrying out of another program to balance 
development of the domestic economy. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS4-53949 </DOCNO>
