<H3> <TI>   Cable TV, Telecom Firms To Study Networks Tie-Up </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Cable TV, Telecom Firms To Study Networks Tie-Up </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   OW2305080294 Tokyo KYODO in English 0733 GMT 23 May 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW2305080294 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo KYODO </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Tokyo, May 23 KYODO -- Twenty-two Japanese firms 
will launch a two-year feasibility study on merging cable 
television networks and telecommunication systems in preparation 
for the forthcoming multimedia era, officials of the organizing 
body said Monday [23 May]. 
  The organizer is the Cable TV Conference, formed by Japan's 
cable TV Industry Association. 
  Using cable TV networks, the organizer seeks to provide a 
wide range of services, starting with personal handyphone 
systems (PHS) initially, and gradually diversifying into 
personal computer communications and broadcast shopping 
information. 
  In the face of rapid technological shifts to multimedia 
communication, the 22 companies, mostly cable TV operators such 
as Tokyu Cable Television Co., and common carriers like DDI 
Corp., want to explore the many possibilities, the officials 
said. 
  The firms also include KDD, NEC Corp. and leading trading 
house Mitsui and Co., they said. 
  Japan's phone services industry is currently dominated by 
Nippon Telegraph and Telephone Corp. (NTT), but the project will 
create another large communications link in the near future, 
they said. 

</TEXT>

