<F P=100> NORTHEAST ASIA </F>
<F P=101> Japan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Commodities Dealers `Illegally' Discounting Commissions </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Commodities Dealers `Illegally' Discounting Commissions </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   OW2305100394 Tokyo KYODO in English 0907 GMT 23 May 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW2305100394 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo KYODO </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Tokyo, May 23 KYODO -- Commodity futures dealers 
have been illegally discounting commissions for large investors 
and foreigners, government sources said Monday [23 May]. 
  The Ministry of International Trade and Industry (MITI) and 
the Ministry of Agriculture, Forestry and Fisheries found in a 
probe that dealers have discounted commissions for futures 
transactions of gold, Azuki beans and other commodities for the 
sake of specific investors in breach of the commodity exchange 
law, government sources said. 
  Officially, however, the ministries deny any such misconduct 
by the dealers, the sources said. The ministries will take no 
particular punitive actions against the dealers. 
  Under the law, the practice of commission discounting is 
banned and violators could face fines or other penalties, 
although no cases of violation have ever been reported. 
  Japan's relatively high commissions -- seven to eight times 
more for gold futures than on the New York market -- puts local 
dealers at a disadvantage in international competition. 
Therefore, it is widely seen as "common sense" among dealers to 
change commissions from customer to customer in order to survive. 
  "We cannot compete unless we discount (commissions)," an 
official with one firm said. 
  Responding to calls from Japanese traders, the government 
plans to partially liberalize the commissions in June. 
  The planned liberalization, however, will be limited to 
commissions for foreign investors and commodity funds apparently 
because sweeping deregulation would hurt smaller dealers, the 
sources said. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS4-53956 </DOCNO>
