<F P=100> NORTHEAST ASIA </F>
<F P=101> Japan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Bank of Japan Says Economy `Poised for Recovery' </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Bank of Japan Says Economy `Poised for Recovery' </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   OW2405072694 Tokyo KYODO in English 0658 GMT 24 May 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW2405072694 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo KYODO </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Tokyo, May 24 KYODO -- Japan's economy is poised 
for recovery but prevailing downward indicators make continued 
caution necessary, Finance Minister Hirohisa Fujii and Bank of 
Japan Governor Yasushi Mieno said Tuesday [24 May]. 
  "The time is ripe for the economy to recover, with personal 
consumption showing improvements," Fujii said in a speech read 
by Vice Finance Minister Jiro Saito at a meeting of the National 
Association of Shinkin Banks. 
  Mieno said, "The economy is showing signs of hitting bottom, 
with some indicators pointing to improvements in economic 
activities led by personal consumption." 
  The central bank chief also cited various factors that 
underscore the improvement of conditions over the same period 
last year when the economy fell off after showing signs of 
recovery. They included progressing inventory adjustments and 
corporate restructuring, the spreading effects of the latest 
fiscal and monetary measures and recovering overseas economies 
led by the United States. 
  Fujii also repeated his "confidence" that the record 15.25 
trillion yen stimulus package launched in February and the 
fiscal 1994 budget would "contribute greatly to putting the 
economy on a full-fledged recovery." But the two financial 
leaders noted that the economy also faces possible downward 
trends. 
  Fujii said, "the economy remains sluggish with tough 
situations prevailing in capital investment and labor." 
  Mieno said, "cautious watching is still necessary" to see if 
the recent improvements are sustainable enough to spread to the 
overall economy. 
  "We must also keep in mind that negative factors prevail," 
he 
said, citing continued volatile currency rates, "strong 
adjustment pressure" on labor, and time needed for balance-sheet 
adjustments by companies and financial institutions after the 
collapse of the "bubble" economy boom in the late 1980s. 
  Regarding exchange rates, the central bank chief said, 
"further careful watching is necessary," suggesting his 
unchanged stance of intervening in currency markets to stem 
excessive volatility. 
  Mieno called for continued positive efforts by banks to 
clear 
nonperforming loans, saying that liquidations are still 
"mid-way," although emergence of new bad loans is slowing down. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

