<H3> <TI>   Further Reportage on Framework Talks With U.S. </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Further Reportage on Framework Talks With U.S. </PHRASE></F></HT>
<H4>    `Make-or-Break' Day Four Talks Described </H4>

<F P=102> OW2305140494 Tokyo KYODO in English 1339 GMT 23 May 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW2305140494 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo KYODO </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Washington, May 23 KYODO -- Negotiations between 
senior Japanese and U.S. officials went into day four Monday for 
what appeared a make-or-break session to seek a breakthrough in 
the stalled "framework" trade talks between the two countries. 
  The talks are now at "a delicate stage," the top Japanese 
Government spokesman, Chief Cabinet Secretary Hiroshi Kumagai, 
said in Tokyo Monday. 
  A top official at the Japanese Foreign Ministry also 
suggested that the talks in Washington have moved into a 
critical stage, saying the two sides will see whether they can 
"make it or not" after Monday's session. 
  Japanese negotiators -- headed by Deputy Foreign Minister 
Sadayuki Hayashi and Vice Minister of International Trade and 
Industry Sozaburo Okamatsu -- headed for the apparent showdown 
on Monday after a top-level government strategy session in Tokyo. 
  Japanese officials said Prime Minister Tsutomu Hata met with 
senior government officials on Monday morning on the trade 
negotiations. 
  "We are vigorously trying to break an impasse in the 
negotiations," Kumagai told reporters in Tokyo following the 
Hata meeting. 
  Japanese Foreign Minister Koji Kakizawa may visit the United 
States, depending on the outcome of Monday's talks, Vice Foreign 
Minister Kunihiko Saito said. 
  Monday's session came after the two sides met for one hour 
Saturday in what officials said was focused on "clarifications" 
on a Japanese position for resuming the trade negotiations under 
the framework agreement concluded last July. 
  The trade talks, which are aimed at widening foreign access 
to the Japanese market and paring down Japan's vast trade 
surplus, broke down in February after Tokyo rejected 
Washington-proposed yardsticks to gauge progress in Japanese 
imports. 
  Among the industry sectors covered under the framework 
accord 
are Japanese Government procurement of medical and 
telecommunications equipment, trade in autos and auto parts and 
the Japanese insurance market. 
  Japanese officials said Eisuke Sakakibara, a senior Finance 
Ministry official in charge of insurance negotiations, headed to 
Washington to help with the talks. 
  No high-ranking officials from the Finance Ministry have 
attended the talks so far. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

