<F P=100> NORTHEAST ASIA </F>
<F P=101> Japan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Further Reportage on Framework Talks With U.S. </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Further Reportage on Framework Talks With U.S. </PHRASE></F></HT>
<H4>    Trade, Industry Minister Cited </H4>

<F P=102> OW2405022794 Tokyo KYODO in English 0208 GMT 24 May 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW2405022794 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo KYODO </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Tokyo, May 24 KYODO -- A breakthrough in deadlocked 
trade "framework" talks between Japan and the United States is 
looming large, International Trade and Industry Minister Eijiro 
Hata said Tuesday. 
  With time left for discussion running out, both parties have 
basically agreed to get the stalled talks on establishing a new 
framework for bilateral trade back on a track, Hata told a press 
conference. 
  Hata said Japanese and U.S. delegates at subcabinet-level 
talks in Washington are now working on the final wording of key 
points that have divided the two parties since the framework 
talks ruptured in February. 
  If the delegates reach specific accords on resuming the 
trade 
talks, that would lead to an early meeting of the leaders of the 
two countries for a final breakthrough in the negotiations, Hata 
said. 
  But Hata declined to speculate when issues hampering a 
restart of the trade talks will be cleared. He denied reports 
that it would be "in one or two days." 
  In Washington, the unofficial trade negotiations entered a 
fourth day, with the sticking point being how to define earlier 
agreed "objective criteria" as a way to gauge U.S. access to 
Japanese markets. 
  "We are working on final wording of such a term so that it 
can be defined in a mutually acceptable manner," Hata said. 
  The talks to establish a new bilateral trade framework broke 
down when Japan rejected a U.S. demand for using "numerical 
targets" as objective criteria during the February summit 
between then Japanese Prime Minister Morihiro Hosokawa and U.S. 
President Bill Clinton. 
  In search of a breakthrough in the talks, Washington made 
three new proposals to Japan in April on three areas -- 
objective criteria, overall goals of the framework talks and 
macroeconomic policy measures. 
  Heading the Japanese team at the Washington talks are 
Sozaburo Okamatsu, vice international trade and industry 
minister for International affairs, and Sadayuki Hayashi, deputy 
foreign minister for economic affairs. They are believed to 
have given Japan's reply to the three U.S. proposals. 

</TEXT>

