<H3> <TI>   Further Reportage on Framework Talks With U.S. </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Further Reportage on Framework Talks With U.S. </PHRASE></F></HT>
<H4>    Hata on Numerical Targets </H4>

<F P=102> OW2405071894 Tokyo KYODO in English 0703 GMT 24 May 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW2405071894 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo KYODO </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Tokyo, May 24 KYODO -- Prime Minister Tsutomu Hata 
said Tuesday the United States is not likely to demand that 
Tokyo set numerical targets to measure progress in opening 
Japanese markets as means of rectifying the chronic bilateral 
trade imbalance. 
  Hata, answering questions at the House of Representatives 
Budget Committee, said Japan and the U.S. have deepened mutual 
understanding through a series of recent contacts on the issue. 
  The premier said vice ministerial-level negotiations in 
Washington on resumption of a new bilateral trade framework have 
neared conclusion, although he has not received a report on the 
results. 
  Japan cannot accept such numerical targets, Hata said, "and 
I 
expect it (the outcome of the negotiations) is not likely to 
have such things." 
  Tokyo has rejected a U.S. demand to introduce such targets, 
which led to a collapse in February's bilateral summit. 
  According to Japanese officials, Japan and the United States 
late Monday resumed long-stalled talks on a new trade framework 
following an agreement that was clinched after four days of 
tough negotiations. 
  They said the results of the agreement will be announced 
Tuesday night Japan time, but they did not provide other details. 
  Hata reiterated that Japan must make efforts to further open 
its market on its own initiative, through deregulation and 
clarifying procedures to access the market. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

