<H3> <TI>   Secret Milk Accords Alleged With Australia, U.S. </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Secret Milk Accords Alleged With Australia, U.S. </PHRASE></F></HT>
<H4>    Bilateral Agreements Said Signed </H4>

<F P=102> OW2405051694 Tokyo KYODO in English 0005 GMT 24 May 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW2405051694 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo KYODO </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Tokyo, May 24 KYODO -- Japan, Australia and the 
United States have forged bilateral accords on milk products in 
the face of liberalization next year, the ASAHI SHIMBUN reported 
Tuesday [24 May]. 
  The leading Japanese daily on its front page said Japan in 
secret bilateral negotiations with Washington in late March 
pledged to import 20,000 to 30,000 tons of milk products 
annually for use in bread and confectioneries through a 
semigovernment channel. 
  The paper reported that the bilateral accord with Australia 
was reached last year. 
  But the Ministry of Agriculture, Forestry and Fisheries 
denied the allegation. "These measures are not a 
country-by-country accord, being prohibited by GATT," the daily 
quoted a ministry official as saying. 
  Japan will liberalize imports of milk products in 1995 with 
a 
minimum foreign access level of 137,202 tons annually under the 
Uruguay Round of the General Agreement on Tariffs and Trade 
(GATT). 
  The amount, which is imported on low tariffs, is allocated 
to 
the Livestock Industry Promotion Corp. The other importers will 
be permitted to buy the foreign farm products at high tariffs. 
  The semigovernment body also promised Australia that it will 
buy three-quarters of Japan's total imports of the allocated 
skim milk and butter annually, according to the daily. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

