<H3> <TI>   Secret Milk Accords Alleged With Australia, U.S. </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Secret Milk Accords Alleged With Australia, U.S. </PHRASE></F></HT>
<H4>    Farm Minister Denies Accords </H4>

<F P=102> OW2405054894 Tokyo KYODO in English 0408 GMT 24 May 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW2405054894 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo KYODO </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Tokyo, May 24 KYODO -- Japan's farm minister denied 
a news report Tuesday that the government has reached secret 
bilateral accords with Australia and the United States to import 
certain amounts of milk products. 
  The report, published in the Japanese daily ASAHI SHIMBUN, 
said the accords were reached in the face of import 
liberalization for the products next year. 
  Agriculture, Forestry and Fisheries Minister Mutsuki Kato 
told reporters that Japan is holding negotiations with the U.S. 
and Australia to guarantee the 1986-1988 level of butter, skim 
milk and other milk product imports. 
  The talks under way do not concern country-by-country 
accords, which are prohibited by the General Agreement on 
Tariffs and Trade (GATT), Kato said. 
  He added that Japan, which is holding the negotiations under 
GATT rules, has no secret deals and has offered no guarantees on 
milk product imports. 
  Kato said that Japan will inform GATT of the results of the 
negotiations when they are completed. 

</TEXT>

