<F P=100> ANNEX </F>
<F P=101> Japan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Hata Backs Cooperation With U.S., ROK on DPRK </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Hata Backs Cooperation With U.S., ROK on DPRK </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   OW2505024994 Tokyo Nikkei Telecom Database in Japanese 25 
May 94--FOR OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> OW2505024994 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo Nikkei Telecom Database </F>
<F P=105>  Japanese </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [From MAINICHI SHIMBUN 25 May Morning Edition] </F>
  [Excerpt] During a 24 May session of the House of 
Representatives Budget Committee, Kazuo Shii of the Japan 
Communist Party said that the United Nations will not adopt a 
resolution slapping economic sanctions on the DPRK for its 
suspected development of nuclear weapons. He then asked Prime 
Minister Hata how Japan will deal with economic sanctions if the 
United States and other nations impose them on North Korea. In 
response, Prime Minister Hata stated: "If the United States and 
other nations impose economic sanctions on the DPRK, Japan would 
prepare for a state of emergency in accordance with the 
Constitution. The economic sanctions imposed by the United 
States and other nations are different from those slapped on by 
the United Nations." In this way, the prime minister indicated 
that Japan can take concerted action with the United States and 
South Korea against North Korea. 
  During the session, however, Prime Minister Hata refused to 
state specifically how Japan will deal with the economic 
sanctions, saying: "Inspectors from the International Atomic 
Energy Agency are now checking nuclear facilities in North 
Korea, and it is a very delicate time. I therefore wish to 
refrain from discussing at this session how Japan should deal 
with the economic sanctions." [passage omitted on questions and 
answers on public services fees at the session] 

</TEXT>

