<H3> <TI>   Komeito Official on Impact of Kaishin Dissolution </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Komeito Official on Impact of Kaishin Dissolution </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   OW2005044894 Tokyo NIHON KEIZAI SHIMBUN in Japanese 19 May 
94 Morning Edition p 2--FOR OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> OW2005044894 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo NIHON KEIZAI SHIMBUN </F>
<F P=105>  Japanese </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] The ruling Democratic Socialist Party [DSP] and the 
ruling New Japan Party are advocating breaking up the unified 
parliamentary group "Kaishin" [Innovation]. Commenting on the 
two ruling parties' move at an 18 May meeting of Komeito 
legislators, Komeito Secretary General Yuichi Ichikawa said: 
"If the two ruling parties, which formed "Kaishin," have 
altered their policies, their leadership cannot escape the 
responsibility." In this way, he indicated that if the 
"Kaishin" is dissolved, Keigo Ouchi, chairman of the DSP; 
Morihiro Hosokawa, representative of the Japan New Party; and 
Ichiro Ozawa, secretary general of Shinseito [Japan Renewal 
Party], would need to step down. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

