<F P=100> ANNEX </F>
<F P=101> Japan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Mori Considers SDPJ-Sakigake-LDP Alliance </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Mori Considers SDPJ-Sakigake-LDP Alliance </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   OW2005023594 Tokyo YOMIURI SHIMBUN in Japanese 19 May 94 
Morning Edition p 3--FOR OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> OW2005023594 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo YOMIURI SHIMBUN </F>
<F P=105>  Japanese </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Yoshiro Mori, secretary general of the opposition 
Liberal Democratic Party [LDP], met with Koichi Kato [former 
chief cabinet secretary), representative of the "New Century 
Group," a suprafaction action group for new policies in the LDP, 
and others at a Tokyo restaurant in the evening of 18 May. 
During the meeting, Mr. Mori said: "If the people ask the LDP 
to forge an alliance with the opposition Social Democratic Party 
of Japan [SDPJ] after the Hata cabinet resigns en masse, the LDP 
would be willing to do so. The LDP also intends to forge an 
alliance with Sakigake [Harbinger Party]." In this way, Mr. 
Mori indicated that the LDP will examine the possibility of 
forging a coalition with the SDPJ and Sakigake after it submits 
a no-confidence motion against the Hata cabinet to the Diet. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS4-54011 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "dreas101__a94019" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-EAS-94-101-A </AU>
Daily Report 
<DATE1>  16 May 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> ANNEX </F>
<F P=101> Japan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Party Officials Interviewed on Political Issues </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Party Officials Interviewed on Political Issues </PHRASE></F></HT>
<H4>    Mirai Party Head on Party Role </H4>

<F P=102> OW2105011494 Tokyo MAINICHI SHIMBUN in Japanese 16 May 94 
Morning Edition p 2--FOR OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> OW2105011494 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo MAINICHI SHIMBUN </F>
<F P=105>  Japanese </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Interview with New Party Mirai (Future) representative </F>
Michihiko Kano by unidentified MAINICHI SHIMBUN reporter: place 
and date not given -- from "Listening Without Reservation" 
column] 
  [Text] [MAINICHI SHIMBUN] You and your colleagues broke 
away from the opposition Liberal Democratic Party [LDP]. Was 
there not a mistake in the timing of your breakaway from the LDP? 
  [Kano] I believe that we quit the LDP at the right time. We 
do not repent of our break from the LDP. 
  [MAINICHI SHIMBUN] Why has your party not joined the new 
parliamentary group "Kaishin"? 
  [Kano] We do not know at all how or why the parliamentary 
group was formed. We just quit the LDP when the parliamentary 
group was formed and we heard nothing from other political 
parties about forming the parliamentary group. Our party could 
not draw a conclusion on whether to join the parliamentary group 
because our party values the process of making decisions through 
discussion. 
  [MAINICHI SHIMBUN] What sort of political tactic do you 
think Prime Minister Hata should adopt? 
  [Kano] In my meeting with Prime Minister Hata, I proposed 
that parties and parliamentary groups that voted for Mr. Hata in 
the prime ministerial election at a Diet plenary session 
assemble to discuss issues, and asked the prime minister to tell 
the assembly what he thinks. However, the prime minister did 
not accept my requests. 
  [MAINICHI SHIMBUN] With a minority in the Diet, the Hata 
government is expected to have difficulty implementing policies 
after a budget bill for fiscal 1994 is enacted in the Diet. 
What is your opinion? 
  [Kano] The Social Democratic Party of Japan [SDPJ] is 
sharing a common perception with other parties on the nine-point 
policy agreement. If the Hata government holds talks with the 
SDPJ to discuss policy matters forthrightly, the SDPJ would 
understand. If both ruling and opposition parties hold frank 
debates on how the current tax system should be reformed to turn 
Japan around, it would be possible to reach an agreement. Both 
ruling and opposition parties should make concerted efforts to 
grapple with the issue of North Korea's suspected development of 
nuclear weapons. 
  [MAINICHI SHIMBUN] What sort of role does the "New Party 
Mirai" intend to play in the future? 
  [Kano] As for reforming the current tax system, our party 
plans to set forth a concrete vision that aims to improve the 
quality of life for the people through tax system reform. 
Regarding the issue of North Korea's suspected development of 
nuclear arms, our party intends to plead with that country to 
remain a nuclear-free nation. Our party also intends to make 
efforts to keep that country from being isolated from the rest 
of the world through diplomatic channels. Our party will 
advocate the need to keep all of Asia nuclear-free. 
  [MAINICHI SHIMBUN] How are you going to increase your 
party's membership? 
  [Kano] Now that the Diet has enacted the political reform 
bill, the next task will be a realignment of the political 
parties. For our party to function properly in this drastically 
changing political situation, our party needs to reorganize 
itself on the basis of policies and political beliefs. Our 
party should set forth a set of new policies while pushing for 
reforms. Many people agree with our party's plans. There are 
many legislators in the LDP with whom I worked for the political 
reform. 
  [MAINICHI SHIMBUN] Do you think that you and Shinseito 
[Japan Renewal Party] representative secretary Ichiro Ozawa are 
of the same political beliefs? 
  [Kano] I do not know all of what Mr. Ozawa thinks. We do 
not share the same views on handling the reforms, but we may 
share views that things must not be deferred until later. 
  [MAINICHI SHIMBUN] What do you think of the possibility of 
dissolving the House of Representatives? 
  [Kano] Our party resolutely opposes holding the next general 
elections under the current multiseat constituency system. What 
is important for us at the moment is to move things forward. 
Why did we spend seven years working for political reform? We 
should not set back political reform. To keep political reform 
on track, we have to speedily draft a bill on the demarcation of 
single-seat constituencies. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS4-54012 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "dreas101__a94020" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-EAS-94-101-A </AU>
Daily Report 
<DATE1>  18 May 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> ANNEX </F>
<F P=101> Japan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Party Officials Interviewed on Political Issues </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Party Officials Interviewed on Political Issues </PHRASE></F></HT>
<H4>    Watanabe on LDP's Position </H4>

<F P=102> OW2005130194 TOKYO ASAHI SHIMBUN in Japanese 18 May 94 
Morning Edition p 7--FOR OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> OW2005130194 </F>
<F P=104>  TOKYO ASAHI SHIMBUN </F>
<F P=105>  Japanese </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Interview with Michio Watanabe, former deputy prime </F>
minister and foreign minister, by unidentified ASAHI SHIMBUN 
reporter; place and date not given] 
  [Text] [ASAHI SHIMBUN] Do you not think that you were 
exploited by Secretary General Ichiro Ozawa of Shinseito [Japan 
Renewal Party] concerning the problem of succession to former 
Prime Minister Morihiro Hosokawa? 
  [Watanabe] There may be various viewpoints. We are 
professionals living in the political world, so it is possible 
that he may have used me as a card to obtain policy concessions 
from the Social Democratic Party of Japan [SDPJ]. However, if 
the SDPJ made a concession because of that, it is good for the 
country, is it not? 
  [ASAHI SHIMBUN] It is said that the Hata administration has 
a dual power structure or that the Hata administration is 
"Ozawa's cabinet." 
  [Watanabe] If a man can be a scenario writer and leading 
actor at the same time like former Prime Minister Kakuei Tanaka, 
it is all right. However, a division of work is necessary to 
some extent. It may be that, since the two men are not 
different in their ideas, tickets will sell well if Hata, not 
Ozawa, dances on the stage. 
  [ASAHI SHIMBUN] Are you still thinking of leaving the LDP if 
that helps to eliminate a policy gap? 
  [Watanabe] The problem is that Shinseito and the LDP are at 
odds with each other despite the fact that their policies are 
almost identical. It will be difficult for the Hata 
administration to implement its policies unless it officially 
asks for the LDP's cooperation. I have been thinking of 
mediating between the two parties. 
  [ASAHI SHIMBUN] Is there any possibility of your leaving the 
LDP if there is a chance of political realignment? 
  [Watanabe] It is too dangerous to make comments on that. 
  [ASAHI SHIMBUN] There is a movement afoot in the LDP to come 
back to power in league with some members of the SDPJ and 
Sakigake [Harbinger]. 
  [Watanabe] Cooperation between the LDP and the SDPJ should 
be limited to the management of Diet affairs. If, however, the 
SDPJ breaks with convention and comes closer to our party in 
policy cooperation than when it formed an alliance with 
Shinseito and other parties, that would be another story. 
  [ASAHI SHIMBUN] What will be the nature of political 
realignment? 
  [Watanabe] I think there will be two lines of thought: one 
based on the main current of the LDP and the other different 
from that. The voluntary establishment of the Constitution is 
the LDP's platform, but we are not saying that we should amend 
Article 9 of the Constitution. It would be ridiculous not to 
discuss the problem of the Constitution since the world is 
changing in many spheres, like the problem of the environment 
and the problem of limiting property rights. 
  [ASAHI SHIMBUN] There is a considerable difference between 
your way of thinking and the contents of LDP President Yohei 
Kono's interpellation at the Diet concerning the problem of 
security. 
  [Watanabe] I am not saying we should approve the exercise of 
the right of collective self-defense. What I am saying is: 
"Concerning UN peacekeeping activities, postwar management and 
attendance for the confiscation of weapons can be interpreted as 
collective security from the standpoint of the Constitution. 
Concerning national emergency laws, laws providing for the 
minimum requirement for security can be made within the 
framework of the Constitution. 
  [ASAHI SHIMBUN] LDP President Yohei Kono has declared that 
he will submit a no-confidence motion against the cabinet in the 
current Diet session. 
  [Watanabe] If a no-confidence motion is to be submitted, 
there must be just cause for it. I am sure of one thing: It is 
not good for a minority government, which does not represent the 
will of the people, to deal with the next budget or to maintain 
a cabinet for a long time. However, if the Hata administration 
asks for our cooperation in pursuing the same policy as the 
LDP's, we cannot submit a no-confidence motion. 
  [ASAHI SHIMBUN] What do you think will happen after a 
no-confidence motion is submitted? 
  [Watanabe] That is impossible to say because there is the 
other party, not just us. Speaking of dissolution by mutual 
consent, for example, it is also impossible to tell whether 
there is mutual consent. It will take time for the current Diet 
to pass bills on redrawing electoral districts, because the 
opinions of local governments must be listened to. And it is 
still unknown whether Prime Minister Hata will choose 
dissolution. 
  [ASAHI SHIMBUN] If the Diet is dissolved before a bill on 
redrawing electoral districts is passed, that constitutes 
"torpedoing political reform," does it not? 
  [Watanabe] At any rate, since the single-seat constituency 
system was enacted by both the ruling and opposition parties, it 
is impossible to abolish it without using it even once. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

