<H3> <TI>   Party Officials Interviewed on Political Issues </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Party Officials Interviewed on Political Issues </PHRASE></F></HT>
<H4>    Rengo Head on Coalition, SDPJ </H4>

<F P=102> OW2505012494 Tokyo ASAHI SHIMBUN in Japanese 21 May 94 
Morning Edition p 7--FOR OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> OW2505012494 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo ASAHI SHIMBUN </F>
<F P=105>  Japanese </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [From the "How Will the Tense Political Situation Change in </F>
the Future?" column; interview with Akira Yamagishi, chairman of 
Rengo (Japanese Trade Union Confederation), by unidentified 
ASAHI SHIMBUN correspondent; place and date not given] 
  [Text] [ASAHI SHIMBUN] The opposition Liberal Democratic 
Party [LDP] appears to be intending to force the Hata cabinet to 
dissolve the House of Representatives and hold a general 
election by submitting to the Diet a vote of no confidence 
against it. What is your opinion? 
  [Yamagishi] The LDP is asserting that the Hata cabinet 
deserves to be voted out of power merely because it is a 
minority government, but I believe that the LDP's assertion 
lacks persuasive force. The opposition Social Democratic Party 
of Japan [SDPJ] has to alter its simple logic that "the enemy of 
my enemy is my friend." 
  [ASAHI SHIMBUN] Some SDPJ members are voicing their support 
for holding the next general election under the current 
multiseat constituency system. What do you think? 
  [Yamagishi] If the next general elections are held under the 
multiseat constituency system, the SDPJ would win some more 
seats in the House of Representatives, but the LDP also would 
increase its seats there. The next general election could be 
held under the multiseat constituency system depending on how 
the political situation develops in the future. I, however, 
believe that it is desirable to hold the next general election 
under a new electoral system. The SDPJ is now at a loss. If 
the SDPJ intends to rally liberal forces, it cannot forge any 
alliance with the LDP. If the SDPJ does not take the position 
of not allowing the LDP to retake power, it would leave ruling 
coalition parties in disarray. 
  [ASAHI SHIMBUN] What about the possibility of the SDPJ 
returning to the ruling coalition? 
  [Yamagishi] I believe that it would be difficult for the 
SDPJ 
to return to the ruling coalition unless a major development 
occurs which makes the people understand its return to the 
ruling coalition. 
  I hope that such a "major development" will occur to open 
the 
way for the SDPJ to return to the ruling coalition. The SDPJ's 
intention of rallying the liberal forces does not contradict its 
return to the ruling coalition. If the SDPJ does everything it 
can to rally the liberal forces, this would cause the "major 
development" to occur. There is no change in the widely held 
impression that the coalition government is shored up by new 
conservative forces and liberal forces. 
  [ASAHI SHIMBUN] What do you mean by the major development? 
May I interpret the major development as the resignation of 
Shinseito [Japan Renewal Party] representative Ichiro Ozawa? 
  [Yamagishi] If I comment publicly on that, it would cause 
confusion and make it hard for the major development to occur. 
  [ASAHI SHIMBUN] The Hata government is shaky because it is a 
minority government. Do you think that the Hata government can 
trigger the major development? 
  [Yamagishi] Given the values and integrity of Prime Minister 
Hata, I cannot rule out that possibility. 
  [ASAHI SHIMBUN] What do you think of Mr. Ozawa? 
  [Yamagishi] I do not know him well, but he is currently 
making a lot of belligerent comments. He imposes his ideas on 
others when he holds a dialogue with them. He is causing human 
relationships to worsen. 
  [ASAHI SHIMBUN] What about the possibility of the SDPJ 
returning to the coalition government? 
  [Yamagishi] The possibility still exists. If the SDPJ clings 
to its own policies, it is doubtful whether it can reach an 
agreement on basic policies with Sakigake [Harbinger]. The SDPJ 
would be isolated from the rest of the political parties in the 
end. 
  [ASAHI SHIMBUN] Will it not difficult for the SDPJ to rally 
the liberal forces prior to the general election? 
  [Yamagishi] If the SDPJ fails to rally the liberal forces 
prior to the general election, it will face self-destruction. 
If only the SDPJ and Sakigake wage a concerted campaign under 
the single-seat constituency system, they will be no match for 
other political parties. A majority of the liberal forces are 
now in the ruling coalition parties, and they are affiliated 
with the Democratic Socialist Party [DSP], the Japan New Party, 
Shinseito, and a splinter group from the LDP. Now is the best 
time for the SDPJ to open the way for concluding a policy 
agreement with those liberal forces, forging an alliance with 
new conservative forces in Shinseito and Komeito, and choosing a 
single candidate to run in the next general election. Hokkaido 
Governor Takahiro Yokomichi and Sakigake representative 
Masayoshi Takemura can take the lead in rallying the liberal 
forces. I think that it is desirable to form a liberal 
coalition policy study group which transcends party affiliations. 
  [ASAHI SHIMBUN] It is whispered that DSP Chairman Keigo 
Ouchi 
will resign as chairman at a party convention scheduled for June. 
  [Yamagishi] Any decisions to be made at the party convention 
will have a great impact on the future of the former ruling 
coalition parties, including the SDPJ. I will pay close 
attention to the party convention. I hope that the DSP will play 
a key role in urging the SDPJ to return to the coalition 
government. 
  [ASAHI SHIMBUN] When are you going to give your approval to 
raising indirect taxes with "some conditions attached?" 
  [Yamagishi] In principle, I do not favor raising any taxes, 
but I intend to urge the Policy Consultative Council formed by 
the SDPJ and the DSP to speedily work out a joint proposal, 
thereby deepening their mutual understanding, and to ask the two 
parties to present the joint proposal to other parties. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

