Daily Report 
<DATE1>  18 May 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> ANNEX </F>
<F P=101> Japan </F>
<H3> <TI>   KDD To Invest in INMARSAT Communications Firm </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    KDD To Invest in INMARSAT Communications Firm </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   942A0242A Tokyo NIKKEI SANGYO SHIMBUN in Japanese 18 May 94 
p 7--FOR OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> 942A0242A </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo NIKKEI SANGYO SHIMBUN </F>
<F P=105>  Japanese </F>


<TEXT>
CSO 

  [Text] The International Marine Satellite Organization 
(INMARSAT) whose membership includes communications companies of 
74 nations will establish a satellite-based mobile 
communications operating firm by the end of 1994. The 
organization had launched a goal to establish a global 
satellite-based cellular telephone service project called 
"INMARSAT P" by the year 2000 and had been conducting a review 
as to whether it should handle the project as a parent-company 
function or under the control of a subsidiary. Kokusai Denshin 
Denwa (KDD) which is Japan's only member of the organization 
intends to invest in the new company. 
  The decision to establish the new company was made at 
INMARSAT's recent board meeting held in London. Further, an 
informal decision has been made to operate the satellite at a 
"medium orbit" of 13,155 kilometers altitude. 
  The new company will first be established with capital 
completely paid for by businesses that are currently members and 
investors in INMARSAT, and its monopolistic characteristic will 
be lessened by subsequent capital contributions of 30 percent by 
businesses that are not members of INMARSAT. INMARSAT P will 
provide telephone, facsimile, and data communications services 
using palm-sized cellular instruments. Its goal is to begin 
services in 1999 or 2000 after an investment of about $2.4 
billion. 
  Several private-sector projects such as Motorola's "Iridium 
Project" are under way to provide global cellular communication 
services. It appears that INMARSAT decided to establish a 
separate company for fear that operation of the proposed system 
by INMARSAT itself might lead to criticism of "unfair 
competition." 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

