<F P=100> ANNEX </F>
<F P=101> Japan </F>
<H3> <TI>   MITI Completes Plans To Deregulate LPG Industry </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    MITI Completes Plans To Deregulate LPG Industry </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   942A0236A Tokyo NIHON KEIZAI SHIMBUN in Japanese 7 May 94 p 
5--FOR OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> 942A0236A </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo NIHON KEIZAI SHIMBUN </F>
<F P=105>  Japanese </F>


<TEXT>
CSO 

  [Text] The Ministry of International Trade and Industry 
[MITI] has completed its plans to deregulate the liquefied 
petroleum gas (LPG) industry and related LPG-handling 
procedures. The "Committee To Study LPG Handling Procedures," a 
private advisory organ of the Environmental Protection and 
Industrial Location Bureau, will be established soon and will be 
charged with the mission of formulating detailed deregulating 
plans by this fall. If all goes well, the "Law Regulating the 
Maintenance and Marketing of LPG" will be revised in fiscal year 
1995. 
  The study committee will revise standards for establishing 
LPG replenishment stations that will become wholesalers of LPG 
and retail outlets and will provide for tanks which are larger 
than those allowed in the past. It will also study relaxation of 
the approval standards for domestic gas appliances. 
  In its International Economic Reform Outline completed at 
the 
end of March, the government announced that it would partially 
relax the maintenance regulations concerning dispensing 
equipment used by LPG sales firms. The government has decided to 
expand the scope of deregulation in that the number of 
LPG-related accidents has trended downward to 115 cases per year 
in the past three years. 
  As many as 35,000 retail outlets handle sales to households 
and they consist primarily of small and midsized firms, 
reflecting slow progress in the consolidation of sales and 
distribution outlets. Thus, it appears the study will be 
designed to relax pertinent regulations, promote lower prices, 
and encourage the reorganization of the LPG industry. 
  Domestic LPG demand for fiscal year 1995 will be about 19.42 
million tons, about 5 percent of primary energy consumption. The 
view is expanding that LPG companies and city gas companies will 
be engaging in a fierce price war because the Gas Business Law 
revision pending in the Diet will relax regulations which 
control entry into large-scale gas businesses. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS4-54024 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "dreas101__a94032" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-EAS-94-101-A </AU>
Daily Report 
<DATE1>  13 May 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> ANNEX </F>
<F P=101> Japan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Trading Firms Expand Presence Throughout Asia </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Trading Firms Expand Presence Throughout Asia </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   942A0235A Tokyo ASAHI SHIMBUN in Japanese 13 May 94 p 
12--FOR OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> 942A0235A </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo ASAHI SHIMBUN </F>
<F P=105>  Japanese </F>


<TEXT>
CSO 

  [Text] Major Japanese trading companies are increasing 
personnel assigned to Asia. The objective is to promote a 
rapidly growing market. Sales handled in the region by trading 
firms represent about one-third of worldwide figures, but 
underlying growth potential is huge and the trading firms have 
reached the assessment that "they have no choice but to boost 
their revenue in Asia." Such moves by trading firms are likely 
to continue into the future despite a trend to otherwise reduce 
overseas personnel assignments as a cost-reduction measure. 
  As of April, Nissho Iwai had 280 personnel assigned to the 
Asia, reflecting an increase of 34 (14 percent) in a one-year 
period. Total personnel assigned overseas is 548, a reduction of 
21 in the same period. The company has adopted a "strategic 
personnel" system under which it assigns individuals for a 
two-year extended temporary duty period as a means of handling 
the need to increase personnel in Asia. Overseas assignment 
expenses were normally absorbed by the respective divisions such 
as steel and machinery in the past, but since such an approach 
would not allow for major increases in overseas assignments, the 
expenses are now accounted for in the company overhead category. 
  Increases are noticeable in China, where the staff has been 
increased by 13 to 49. Staffing in Vietnam has been roughly 
doubled to 21, the largest for an integrated trading company. 
The company has opened an office staffed with local personnel at 
the Pun Tao oil transmission station in southern Vietnam which 
is engaged in the development of energy resources. Personnel 
have also been assigned to Kazakhstan and Kyrgyztan. 
  Sumitomo increased Asia region staffing to 209 (20 percent) 
in one year. Increased staffing included 13 for China, five each 
for Thailand and Indonesia, and three each for Hong Kong and 
Vietnam. The additional personnel were noticeable in the 
industrial infrastructure area and handle items such as plants, 
communications, electronics, and aircraft. Half of the overseas 
assignment expenses were charged to headquarters in order to 
alleviate the burden on each of the operating divisions. A vice 
president was placed in charge of the Asia region to strengthen 
control over regional activities. 
  Marubeni increased Asian regional staffing to 266 or by 10. 
Staffing in Vietnam was roughly doubled to 6 in Ho Chi Minh city 
and 5 in Hanoi. Further, the senior individual assigned to 
Vietnam and India was raised in rank to that of representative 
director. 
  Other trading firms are making similar moves. Profits being 
reaped by the trading firms are sizeable in Asia, rendering the 
situation such that they will equal or exceed those being 
realized in Europe and the United States, where business has 
been declining. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS4-54025 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "dreas101__a94033" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-EAS-94-101-A </AU>
Daily Report 
<DATE1>  12 May 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> ANNEX </F>
<F P=101> Japan </F>
<H3> <TI>   NEDO Awards Environment Project to Nippon Steel </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    NEDO Awards Environment Project to Nippon Steel </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   942A0234A Tokyo NIKKEI SANGYO SHIMBUN in Japanese 12 May 94 
p 5--FOR OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> 942A0234A </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo NIKKEI SANGYO SHIMBUN </F>
<F P=105>  Japanese </F>


<TEXT>
CSO 

  [Text] The New Energy and Industrial Technology Development 
Organization (NEDO) recently selected a contractor to handle the 
transfer of environmental technology to developing nations under 
the project titles of "model projects for energy conservation" 
and "projects to assist in the introduction of coal utilization 
systems compatible with the environment." The energy 
conservation projects will be handled by five firms including 
Nippon Steel, while the coal utilization projects will be 
handled by seven firms, including Mitsubishi Heavy Industries. 
The respective firms have targeted fiscal year 1996 as the time 
by which they will demonstrate the commercial feasibility of 
technology for recycling heat produced as a by-product and 
removal of sulfuric contaminants, environmental technologies 
tailored for developing nations. 
  The energy-conservation model project will involve the 
effective use of heat generated in the use of coal at steel 
plants to operate power-generating plant boilers. Japanese firms 
to participate in the project will include Ishikawajima-Harima 
Heavy Industries and Chiyoda Corporation, in addition to Nippon 
Steel. 
  Coal utilization technology will involve the development of 
low-cost sulphur removal systems and high-efficiency boilers to 
be installed in China, the Philippines, and Indonesia. Technical 
development work will be handled by seven firms, including 
Mitsubishi Heavy Industries, Kawasaki Heavy Industries, and 
Ebara Corporation. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS4-54026 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "dreas101__a94034" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-EAS-94-101-A </AU>
Daily Report 
<DATE1>  2 May 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> ANNEX </F>
<F P=101> Japan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Honda Group Develops Lithium Ion Battery Material </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Honda Group Develops Lithium Ion Battery Material </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   942A0233A Tokyo NIKKEI SANGYO SHIMBUN in Japanese 2 May 94 p 
3--FOR OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> 942A0233A </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo NIKKEI SANGYO SHIMBUN </F>
<F P=105>  Japanese </F>


<TEXT>
CSO 

  [Text] A research group composed of Honda Motor's research 
and development subsidiary Honda Technical Research Center and 
fellow researchers led by professor Morinobu Endo of Shinshu 
University's engineering faculty has succeeded in developing an 
electrode material which triples the capacity of lithium ion 
batteries which are considered promising as an energy source for 
next-generation portable electronic equipment. The development 
enables the absorption of lithium ion to a level three times 
that which was believed to be the theoretical limit in the past, 
providing for the fabrication of batteries that are small and of 
high energy density. Its potential applications include portable 
computer equipment and as an electrical energy source for 
electric vehicles. 
  The newly developed carbon material was synthesized by 
applying heat at 700 degrees centigrade to a synthetic material 
called poly (p-phenylene) with a series of benzine rings linked 
in pairs. Most commercially produced batteries contain a 
material which is crystallized graphite, but the new material is 
like an amorphous substance. 
  The electrical capacity of a lithium ion battery is 
determined by the amount of lithium ion stored in the cathode. 
The research group hardened the new material using a 
polyethylene binder, fabricated it into cathodes and immersed 
them together with anodes in hexafluorphosphate electrolyte in 
investigating its characteristics as a storage battery. 
  The battery was charged to a level of 1,000 amperes per one 
kilogram of electrode, enabling the discharge of 680 ampere 
hours at a one- to three-volt range. The electrical current 
density which indicates the discharge speed was recorded at 1.6 
milliampere per one square centimeter of electrode which is an 
order of magnitude faster than current batteries. An examination 
of the electrodes revealed no lattice images on metal lithium, 
confirmed the absorption within the electrodes of lithium ion in 
quantities equal to that reached when the battery is charged to 
a level of 1,000 ampere hours per kilogram of electrode at a 
one- to three-volt range. In the past, the chemical structure of 
lithium was such that the theoretical capacity was considered to 
be limited to 372 ampere hours. 
  A disadvantage with batteries using cathodes made of the new 
material is that it is not capable of producing instantaneous 
bursts of high voltage. Presently, only two times the 
theoretical limit of lithium ion is being used in charging the 
battery, but in the future, it appears that it will become 
feasible to use the full lithium ion capacity of the new battery 
as a result of determining characteristics of the discharge 
mechanism. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

