<F P=100> North Korea </F>
<H3> <TI>   Pakistani Committee for POW Repatriation Formed </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Pakistani Committee for POW Repatriation Formed </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   SK2405133894 Pyongyang KCNA in English 1020 GMT 24 May 94 </F>
<F P=103> SK2405133894 </F>
<F P=104>  Pyongyang KCNA </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Pyongyang, May 24 (KCNA) -- The Pakistan committee 
for support to the repatriation of unconverted long-term 
prisoners in South Korea to the North was inaugurated in Karachi 
on May 15. 
  At the inaugural meeting, chairman of the Pakistan committee 
for supporting the proposal to found the democratic confederal 
republic of Koryo B.M. Kutti was elected chairman of the 
new-born committee and secretary of the Karachi branch of 
the Pakistan-Korea Friendship Association Abdul Malik 
secretary of the committee. 
  At the first session of the committee, the participants 
noted 
that there are many unconverted long-term prisoners in South 
Korea who were taken prisoner during the Korean war and that 
they have been kept under detention for more than 40 years for 
their refusal to be converted. 
  They urged the South Korean authorities to immediately 
return 
to the DPRK Kim In-so and Ham Se-hwan who spent long years in 
prison, refusing ideological conversion, and called on the 
peoples of Pakistan and the world and international human rights 
organisations to wage an international solidarity movement for 
their repatriation. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

